Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Written by
Author: Edgar Allan Poe
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 7/20/2026
Notes: Gothic period live-action, mid-19th century; candlelight, deep shadows, desaturated palette. One medium throughout.

FADE IN:

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

A bare, lamplit chamber. Close walls. A plain wooden chair faces us.

NARRATOR sits in it — a lean man of middle years, pale skin, dark hair disordered, waistcoat unbuttoned at the throat, eyes too bright. He leans forward as if answering an unseen accuser. Period dress; no modern detail.

NARRATOR
True!—nervous—very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am; but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses—not destroyed—not dulled them. Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken! and observe how healthily—how calmly I can tell you the whole story.

He steadies his hands on his knees. A thin smile.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
It is impossible to say how first the idea entered my brain; but once conceived, it haunted me day and night. Object there was none. Passion there was none. I loved the old man. He had never wronged me. He had never given me insult. For his gold I had no desire. I think it was his eye! yes, it was this!

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

OLD MAN sits by a shuttered window — elderly, thin, white hair, dressing gown. He turns. One pale blue eye shows a milky film: the vulture eye.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He had the eye of a vulture—a pale blue eye, with a film over it. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold.

NARRATOR — younger in bearing only by composure, same face and waistcoat — freezes in the doorway under that gaze. His blood drains from his face.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And so by degrees—very gradually—I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
Now this is the point. You fancy me mad. Madmen know nothing. But you should have seen me. You should have seen how wisely I proceeded—with what caution—with what foresight—with what dissimulation I went to work! I was never kinder to the old man than during the whole week before I killed him.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - DAY

Morning light through a crack in the shutters. NARRATOR enters boldly with a tray, hearty, smiling. OLD MAN in bed, the filmed eye half-lidded.

NARRATOR
And how have you passed the night, my good old man?

OLD MAN
Well enough. Well enough.

NARRATOR sets the tray with care. Pats the coverlet. The kindness is perfect — and false.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
So you see he would have been a very profound old man, indeed, to suspect that every night, just at twelve, I looked in upon him while he slept.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S DOOR - NIGHT

A dark lantern in NARRATOR's hand, fully closed. Midnight hush. He turns the latch — oh, so gently — and opens the door a hand's breadth.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Pitch black. Shutters close-fastened. NARRATOR eases his head through the opening, then the dark lantern, closed so no light spills. He moves with agonizing slowness.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha!—would a madman have been so wise as this?

A single thin ray as he undoes the lantern a hair — hinges threaten to creak. The ray seeks the pillow.

The OLD MAN's eye is closed in sleep.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
And this I did for seven long nights—every night just at midnight—but I found the eye always closed; and so it was impossible to do the work; for it was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye.

He withdraws. The door eases shut.

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
Upon the eighth night I was more than usually cautious in opening the door. A watch's minute hand moves more quickly than did mine. Never before that night had I felt the extent of my own powers—of my sagacity. I could scarcely contain my feelings of triumph.

INT. HALL OUTSIDE OLD MAN'S DOOR - NIGHT

NARRATOR at the latch again. Sweat at his temple. He chuckles under his breath — a tiny sound — and freezes.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

On the bed, OLD MAN stirs suddenly, as if startled.

NARRATOR's head is already in. He does not draw back. He pushes the door on steadily, steadily. Black as pitch.

His thumb slips on the tin fastening of the lantern.

A small metallic click.

OLD MAN
(sitting bolt upright)
Who's there?

Silence. NARRATOR does not move a muscle. Does not breathe.

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
I kept quite still and said nothing. For a whole hour I did not move a muscle, and in the meantime I did not hear him lie down. He was still sitting up in the bed listening;—just as I have done, night after night, hearkening to the death watches in the wall.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

OLD MAN upright in the dark, listening. Time stretches. A slight groan — low, stifled — mortal terror, not pain.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I knew the sound well. Many a night, just at midnight, when all the world slept, it has welled up from my own bosom. I knew what the old man felt, and pitied him, although I chuckled at heart.

OLD MAN
(whispering to himself)
It is nothing but the wind in the chimney—it is only a mouse crossing the floor... It is merely a cricket which has made a single chirp.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
All in vain; because Death, in approaching him had stalked with his black shadow before him, and enveloped the victim.

NARRATOR, head still within the room, waits. Patient. Then — stealthily — opens a very little crevice in the lantern.

A single dim ray, like the thread of a spider, shoots out and falls full upon the vulture eye.

It is open — wide, wide open.

NARRATOR's face in the spill of light: fury rising.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I saw it with perfect distinctness—all a dull blue, with a hideous veil over it that chilled the very marrow in my bones; but I could see nothing else of the old man's face or person: for I had directed the ray as if by instinct, precisely upon the damned spot.

A low, dull, quick sound — such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. The beating of the OLD MAN's heart.

It quickens. Louder. Louder.

NARRATOR holds the lantern motionless. Scarcely breathes. The hellish tattoo grows.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
The old man's terror must have been extreme! It grew louder, I say, louder every moment!—do you mark me well? And now at the dead hour of the night, amid the dreadful silence of that old house, so strange a noise as this excited me to uncontrollable terror.

He refrains still — some minutes longer — standing frozen while the beat fills the dark.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I thought the heart must burst. And now a new anxiety seized me—the sound would be heard by a neighbour! The old man's hour had come!

With a loud yell NARRATOR throws open the lantern and leaps into the room.

OLD MAN shrieks once — once only.

NARRATOR drags him to the floor and pulls the heavy bed over him. Then stands, smiling gaily.

Beneath the overturned bed: a muffled heartbeat. On and on.

NARRATOR listens, head tilted. He does not vex. He waits.

For many minutes the muffled sound continues. NARRATOR does not move. A long while. The beat slows... thins... and at length ceases.

He removes the bed. Examines the corpse. Places his hand upon the heart and holds it there — many minutes. No pulsation.

NARRATOR
Stone. Stone dead. His eye would trouble me no more.

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

Candlelight. NARRATOR works hastily, in silence. A tub stands ready. He dismembers the corpse — head, arms, legs — methodical, wary. No blood-spot reaches the floor; the tub catches all.

He pries up three planks from the flooring, deposits the remains between the scantlings, replaces the boards so cunningly that the seams vanish under his palm.

NARRATOR
(soft, delighted)
Ha! ha!

He smooths the boards. Nothing wrong. Nothing to wash out.

A distant BELL sounds four.

INT. STREET DOOR - NIGHT

Still dark as midnight. A knocking at the street door.

NARRATOR descends with a light heart and opens.

Three men in police coats and hats: OFFICER REYNOLDS (senior, calm), OFFICER HAYES (broad, watchful), OFFICER CLEMM (younger, notebook). Perfect suavity.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
A shriek was heard by a neighbour during the night. Suspicion of foul play has been aroused. We have been deputed to search the premises.

NARRATOR smiles — for what has he now to fear?

NARRATOR
Gentlemen—welcome. The shriek was my own, in a dream. The old man is absent in the country. Search—search well.

INT. HALL AND SITTING ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR leads them through with easy hospitality. Lamps raised. Cupboards opened. Nothing amiss.

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR ushers them in. Shows the old man's treasures — secure, undisturbed. In the enthusiasm of his confidence he brings chairs and places them.

He sets his own seat deliberately upon the very boards beneath which the corpse reposes. Sits.

NARRATOR
Rest from your fatigues. You see how it is.

OFFICER REYNOLDS
We are obliged.

The OFFICERS sit. They chat of familiar things. NARRATOR answers cheerily. Singularly at ease.

Then — a change. He pales. A hand to his temple.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Ere long, I felt myself getting pale and wished them gone. My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears: but still they sat and still chatted.

The ringing becomes more distinct. He talks more freely to shake it off. It gains definiteness — until he knows the noise is not within his ears.

A low, dull, quick sound — as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. From under the floor. From under his chair.

NARRATOR gasps for breath. The OFFICERS hear it not. They smile. They chat on.

NARRATOR
(more quickly, vehemently)
—and as I say, the whole matter is nothing, nothing at all—

He rises. Argues about trifles in a high key, violent gesticulations. The noise steadily increases.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
Why—why do you linger over such trifles? Surely you are satisfied—

He paces the floor with heavy strides. Foams. Raves. Swears. Swings his chair and grates it upon the boards — but the noise arises over all.

Louder — louder — louder.

OFFICER HAYES and OFFICER CLEMM exchange a pleasant glance. OFFICER REYNOLDS smiles, unhurried.

NARRATOR
(internal agony breaking through)
Was it possible they heard not?—no, no! They heard!—they suspected!—they knew!—they were making a mockery of my horror!

He cannot bear the hypocritical smiles. The beat pounds — again — louder — louder — louder — louder!

NARRATOR
(shrieking)
Villains! dissemble no more! I admit the deed!—tear up the planks!—here, here!—It is the beating of his hideous heart!

He stabs a finger at the floorboards beneath his feet.

The OFFICERS rise. The pleasant masks fall. OFFICER REYNOLDS looks down at the planks. OFFICER HAYES already moves toward them.

NARRATOR stands over the spot, spent, eyes wide — the sound still hammering in the silence that follows his cry.

INT. CONFESSION ROOM - NIGHT

NARRATOR in the chair again. Spent. Staring at us. The lamp gutters.

He says nothing more.

FADE OUT.

THE END
